-- South African Stocks Rise Most in a week, Led by Anglo, BHP, Famous Brands
-- Ron Derby
-- 2010-08-02T16:13:16Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-02/south-african-stocks-rise-most-in-a-week-led-by-anglo-bhp-famous-brands.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rallied 527.98, or 1.9 percent, to close at
28,883.19 at 5 p.m. in Johannesburg, the biggest advance in
almost a month.  
 The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  
 Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up almost 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark
stock index, rose 9.54 rand, or 3.3 percent, to 302.99 rand, the
biggest gain since June 14. Copper increased as much as 2.5
percent to $7,482 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange.  BHP
Billiton Ltd.  climbed 8.34 rand, or 3.7 percent, to 233.69 rand,
the highest closing price since April 29.  
 Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the largest producer of the
metal, rose 25 rand, or 3.6 percent, to 728 rand.  Impala
Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the world’s second-biggest
platinum producer, advanced 4.51 rand, or 2.3 percent, to 202
rand. Platinum for immediate delivery jumped as much as 1.7
percent to $1,598.75 in London.  
 Blue Financial Services Ltd.  (BFS SJ), a South African
provider of unsecured loans, rallied 1 cent, or 9.1 percent, to
12 cents, paring a 15 percent decline on July 30. The company
said Chief Executive Officer  Dave van Niekerk  quit and that
Chairman  Sipho Twala  will act as interim CEO.  
 Cashbuild Ltd.  (CSB SJ), the building materials retailer,
fell 2 rand, or 2.7 percent, to 71 rand, the biggest decline
since May 7. The company is disappointed with the growth in
revenue during the fourth quarter, it said in a stock-exchange
filing today.  
 Coal of Africa Ltd.  (CZA SJ), the mining company, advanced
80 cents, or 7.3 percent, to 11.70 rand, paring a 9.9 percent
decline on July 30. The company will seek an “immediate
meeting” with South African Mines Minister Buyelwa Sonjica
after comments attributed to her in a report by Reuters that
Coal of Africa was engaged in “illegal activities.”  
 Famous Brands Ltd.  (FBR SJ), a South African company that
operates fast-food chains, advanced 45 cents, or 1.4 percent, to
33.70 rand, the highest price since at least November 1994 when
Bloomberg started tracking the stock. The company agreed to buy
Giramundo, adding flame-grilled chicken to its group of outlets.  
 Old Mutual Plc  (OML SJ), the biggest insurer in Africa,
rose 40 cents, or 2.9 percent, to 14.40 rand, the highest close
since Nov. 25.  Nedbank Group Ltd.  (NED SJ), which is controlled
by Old Mutual, said it may benefit if the insurer were to sell
its stake in the fourth-largest bank. Nedbank gained 1.63 rand,
or 1.2 percent, to 136.84 rand.  
